{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1781507391,"nonce":"0DDQlPGbaTKvsvuEgwkH6Xh+yUE=","title":"There's no way to declare a **partial / filtered unique index** — a `UNIQUE`","message":"constraint that only applies to rows matching a predicate. This is the standard\nPostgres idiom for soft-delete: a slug/email should be unique among *live* rows but\nreusable once a row is soft-deleted.\n\nToday `#[column(unique)]` (and `#[unique(columns = [..])]`) emit an unconditional\n`UNIQUE` constraint, which forbids reusing a value even after the original row is\nsoft-deleted.\n\n\nA way to attach a predicate to a unique column/constraint, e.g.\n\n```\nslug: C::Type\u003c'scope, String\u003e,\n```\n\nrendering:\n\n```sql\nCREATE UNIQUE INDEX uq_organizations_slug\n    ON catalog.organizations (slug)\n    WHERE deleted_at IS NULL;\n```\n\n(Equivalently a table-level form for composite partial uniques, e.g.\n`#[unique(columns = [organization_id, slug], where = ...)]`.)\n\n\nEnforce uniqueness in application code (check-then-insert, filtering out\nsoft-deleted rows). Correct for the soft-delete semantics, but loses the DB-level\nintegrity guarantee and has a check-then-insert race.\n\n\ngitana catalog: organizations / users / repositories are soft-deleted and must allow\nslug/email reuse after deletion. The conformance suite exercises \"soft-delete frees\nthe slug\", which a plain `UNIQUE(slug)` constraint fails. Removed the DB unique\nconstraints and enforce in code for now; a partial unique index would restore\nDB-level integrity.","files":null}]}